docs.abstract: The chain of record stores run by Russ Solomon, who died on Sunday at 92, defined the retail music business in the predigital era, with stars and fans embracing its slogan: “No Music, No Life.”
docs.snippet: The chain of record stores run by Russ Solomon, who died on Sunday at 92, defined the retail music business in the predigital era, with stars and fans embracing its slogan: “No Music, No Life.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Russ Solomon, who died on Sunday at 92, created what for many music fans was the ultimate music emporium: Tower Records, whose yellow-and-red color scheme, “No Music, No Life” slogan, and wide aisles stocked with LPs and CDs defined the retail music business in the pre-digital era. At its peak, the chain had nearly 200 stores in 15 countries and more than $1 billion in annual sales, before debt and shifting consumer habits forced it to close in 2006.

headline.print_headline: ‘No Music, No Life’ For a Record Empire
